    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-31T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-31T07:00:00-05:00" n="766"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d766">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857Ar1/48</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-31T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1915, 1 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received September 1, 12.38 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2809. I believe that German Government is anxious that <hi rend="italic"
                        >Arabic</hi> case should not have <hi rend="italic">Lusitania</hi> case
                    brought in with it. It is easier for the Government to base its concessions on
                        <hi rend="italic">Arabic</hi> case because <hi rend="italic">Arabic</hi> was
                    going west and carried no ammunition. Popular feeling has been worked on because
                    of <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von Tirpitz</persName> party making the
                    situation difficult for Chancellor. Above information given me by friend who has
                    many acquaintances in Reichstag, not in any way from Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
